body:
- Copilot Chat Extension Version: Latest (built from `main`, May 2026)
- VS Code Version: Insiders / built from `main`
- OS Version: Windows 11
- Feature: Model picker / session type switching
- Selected model: Any explicitly selected model (e.g., GPT-4.1)
- Logs: N/A — root cause identified in source

## Description

When switching between chat session types (e.g., Panel ↔ CLI), the user's explicitly selected model is silently and permanently overwritten in persistent storage. Restarting VS Code does not recover it.

The practical impact: the user returns to an existing chat session, doesn't notice the model picker changed, sends their next message — and unknowingly uses a different (potentially weaker or smaller-context) model. If the new model has a smaller context window, this can trigger a conversation compaction that permanently degrades the session's context quality. There's no notification that the model changed, so the user only notices when responses get worse.

## Steps to Reproduce

1. Open VS Code Chat (Panel session type)
2. Explicitly select a model (e.g., GPT-4.1) — this writes to `chat.currentLanguageModel.panel.copilot` via `setCurrentLanguageModel()`
3. View a Copilot CLI session (session type changes to `copilotcli`)
4. Navigate back to the Panel session
5. **Expected:** Model picker shows GPT-4.1 (restored from per-type storage key)
6. **Actual:** Model picker shows whatever model the CLI session last used (e.g., `auto`), and the stored preference is permanently overwritten

## Root Cause

In `chatInputPart.ts` ~line 2122, the `onDidChangeViewModel` handler runs `initSelectedModel()` followed by `preselectModelFromSessionHistory()` unconditionally:

```typescript
// Before fix
if (e.currentSessionResource && newSessionType !== this._currentSessionType) {
    this._currentSessionType = newSessionType;
    this.initSelectedModel();
    this.checkModelInSessionPool();
    this.checkModeInSessionPool();
}
this.preselectModelFromSessionHistory(); // ← runs unconditionally, even after initSelectedModel
```

The call sequence during a session type switch:

1. `initSelectedModel()` reads the per-type storage key (`getSelectedModelStorageKey()` returns e.g., `chat.currentLanguageModel.panel.copilot`) and correctly restores the user's preference
2. `preselectModelFromSessionHistory()` then reads the last model from the session's request history (which belongs to the *previous* session type) and calls `setCurrentLanguageModel()` — overwriting what `initSelectedModel()` just restored
3. `setCurrentLanguageModel()` writes to persistent storage, so the corruption survives restarts

The storage key mechanism (`getSelectedModelStorageKey()`) already correctly scopes preferences per session type. The issue is purely that `preselectModelFromSessionHistory()` runs after `initSelectedModel()` during session type transitions and doesn't respect the distinction.

## Proposed Fix

Move `preselectModelFromSessionHistory()` into an `else` branch so it only runs when the session type did **not** change:

```typescript
if (e.currentSessionResource && newSessionType !== this._currentSessionType) {
    this._currentSessionType = newSessionType;
    this.initSelectedModel();
    this.checkModelInSessionPool();
    this.checkModeInSessionPool();
} else {
    // Only when session type did NOT change — during session type switches,
    // initSelectedModel already restores the user's stored preference and
    // preselectModelFromSessionHistory would overwrite it.
    this.preselectModelFromSessionHistory();
}
```

This preserves `preselectModelFromSessionHistory()`'s intended behavior for same-type session switches (resuming with the model from the last request in that session) while preventing cross-type contamination. No new logic — just an `else` gate.

Will submit a PR with the fix and regression tests.
